org.apache.felix.ipojo.extender

Interface DeclarationBuilderService

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    DefaultDeclarationBuilderService

    public interface DeclarationBuilderService
    This service provides a way for users to manage declarations through code. Notice that produced declarations are immutable once build. But it is possible to re-use a builder to share some configuration through instances. 
         // Obtain the service through the service registry
     DeclarationBuilderService service = ...

     // Get a fresh instance builder
     DeclarationBuilder builder = service.newInstance("the.full.name.of.the.component.to.instantiate");

     DeclarationHandle handle = builder.name("a-unique-name") // Make sure name is unique for the expected type
                                       .configure()
                                           .property("a-property", "a-value")
                                           .property("another-property", "another-value")
                                           .build();

     // Push the InstanceDeclaration service in the registry
     handle.publish();
    Except the InstanceBuilder.build() call, all methods are optional:
    • InstanceBuilder.name(String): if no name is provided, a default one will be generated by iPOJO.
    • InstanceBuilder.version(String): if no version is provided, the first un-versioned type will be used.
    • InstanceBuilder.configure(): if no configuration is required, can be omitted.
    • InstanceBuilder.type(String): can be used to change the required component type.
    • InstanceBuilder#context(org.osgi.framework.BundleContext): by default, the bundle context used to register the created Declaration is the one of the caller. It can be changed though this method.
    Once an instance handle has been created, its configuration (name, type, version and properties) is immutable. It can only be published (so that the framework will try to instantiate the instance) or retracted (framework will remove the instance). Notice that all created instances will appear as "coming from" the bundle that requires the DeclarationBuilderService service. Just like having a metadata.xml file in your bundle that declares your instances. It is possible to override this default behavior using InstanceBuilder#context(org.osgi.framework.BundleContext).
    Since:
    1.11.2
    See Also:
    InstanceDeclaration, TypeDeclaration, ExtensionDeclaration, InstanceBuilder, ConfigurationBuilder, DeclarationHandle
